data:
The N stage is determined by the presence and extent of cancer cells in regional lymph nodes.
The absence of cancer cells in regional lymph nodes corresponds to an N0 stage.
The presence of cancer cells in regional lymph nodes corresponds to an N1, N2, or N3 stage, depending on the number and location of the affected lymph nodes.
The N stage should be determined based on the pathological examination of regional lymph nodes, not on imaging studies or clinical assessments.
Substaging information, such as the number of positive lymph nodes or the ratio of metastatic deposits to the total number of examined lymph nodes, is not considered in determining the N stage for this specific case.
